      %p
        The simulations were carried out for about 1 million femtoseconds (a nanosecond) in
        the case when the gravity is turned on, and for about 2 million femtoseconds in the
        case of zero gravity. The result of the first simulation seems clear --- there is an
        evident difference between the measured partial pressures that is caused by buoyancy.
        The result of the second simulation shows that some small difference between the
        measured partial pressures, which should ideally be exactly identical. To get some
        more confidence for this result, we also provide the result for the partial pressures
        in the time window from 0 to 1 nanosecond, which shows that the small disagreement
        should probably be considered as normal fluctuations for such a small system instead
        of a serious disagreement with the theory. On the same page where that result is
        displayed, we also show the perfect energy conservation graphs for the simulations of
        both situations, which is a convincing evidence indicating that everything has gone
        well in both simulations.
